    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1983-04-06T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1983-04-06T16:00:00-05:00" n="59"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                <head>59. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d59fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Not for the System Documents, 1979–1989, Lot
                        92D630, Not for the System, April 1–15 1983. Secret. In the upper right-hand
                        margin, an unknown hand wrote: “Original Carried to White House by the
                        Secretary on 4/7/83.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1983-04-06T16:00:00-05:00">April 6, 1983, 4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[<hi rend="roman">Omitted here is information unrelated to human
                    rights.</hi>]</p>
                <p>It was therefore agreed that Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> should call in <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> this week to express our satisfaction with the
                    Pentecostalists events<note n="2" xml:id="d59fn2">The Soviet Government
                        permitted the emigration of several of the Pentecostals who had approached
                        the U.S. Embassy in Moscow in early 1983.</note> and to lay on the table
                    four proposed courses of action:</p>
                <p>1. Negotiation of a long-term grain agreement.</p>
                <p>2. Conversations on arms control between <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName> with
                    Rowny present for <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> talks, Nitze for
                        <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> talks, and Abramowitz for <gloss
                        target="#t_MBFR_1">MBFR</gloss> talks. These would be probing discussions to
                    see if any progress can be made at respective negotiation tables.</p>
                <p>3. Probing discussions on regional issues (Afghanistan, Poland, Kampuchea, etc.)
                    by Ambassador Hartman in Moscow.</p>
                <p>4. Progress on our human rights agenda, particularly emigration of the remainder
                    of the embassy Pentecostalists, Soviet Jewry emigration and Poland.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d59fn3">Memoranda of conversations between <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1"
                            >Dobrynin</persName> regarding these four issues are scheduled for
                        publication in <ref target="frus1981-88v04">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1981–1988, vol. IV, Soviet
                            Union, January 1983–March 1985</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[<hi rend="roman">Omitted here is information unrelated to human rights.]</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
